#compdef min
# =============================================================================
# min — a small but practical concatenative programming language and shell.
#       Created by Fabio Cevasco (h3rald) in 2014, min is in the FORTH/JOY/
#       FACTOR family of stack-based concatenative languages but with
#       modern affordances: a managed module manager (MMM), batteries-
#       included stdlib (HTTP/JSON/crypto/dates/regex/sqlite), a built-in
#       interactive REPL with line editing, and an interactive shell mode
#       for scripting daily tasks the way bash/zsh do — but with min's
#       point-free programming style.
#
# Author:  Fabio Cevasco (h3rald)
# Source:  https://github.com/h3rald/min
# CLI:     min.nim (uses Nim's stdlib std/parseopt)
# Library: Nim std/parseopt
#          (Nim standard library's command-line option parser)
# License: MIT
# Status:  Active — 341+ stars, mature language with extensive
#          documentation site at https://min-lang.org and a curated
#          module registry at https://mmm.h3rald.com.  Used by h3rald
#          and a small community for scripting, static site generation
#          (h3rald uses it for his own site), and as a teaching
#          language for stack-based programming.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — MIN IS NOW LANGUAGE 55
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy crosses from
# 54 to 55 documented languages.  min joins the canonical roster alongside:
# Rust, Go, TypeScript-Node, Python, Ruby, Perl, C, C++, Lua, Java, Kotlin,
# Scala, Haskell, OCaml, Elixir, Erlang, Clojure, Common Lisp, Scheme/Racket,
# Julia, Crystal, Pony, Nim, Zig, V, Swift, R, Dart, Fortran, Tcl, Ada, Janet,
# D, Picat, BQN, Frege, Lobster, Curry, Mercury, Wren, Idris2, F#, Jakt,
# Ur/Web, Beluga, REBOL, Io, Pure, Yeti, Whiley, Boogie, Beef, Luau, Tact,
# and now min.  min is documented as the FIRST min CLI library variant in
# the taxonomy (Nim std/parseopt OptParser stdlib library used via min.nim
# bootstrap, with kind/key/val iterator pattern) — bringing the total to
# 228 cross-language CLI library variants.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS MIN AND WHY DOES IT WARRANT ITS OWN CLI LIBRARY DOCUMENTATION CATEGORY?
#
# min is a CONCATENATIVE PROGRAMMING LANGUAGE — the family that includes
# Forth (Charles Moore, 1970), Joy (Manfred von Thun, 2001), and Factor
# (Slava Pestov, 2003).  In concatenative programming, composition is
# function composition: writing two function names side by side composes
# them, no parentheses needed.  The data is on an implicit stack;
# functions read from and write to the stack.
#
# Example min code:
#
#     "Hello, World!" puts          ; pushes "Hello, World!" then puts it
#     1 2 + dup * print              ; (1+2)^2 → 9, prints 9
#     ('hello 'world) ' puts foreach ; print each element of list
#
# Read right-to-left for "what happens when":
#   - `1 2 +` pushes 1, pushes 2, then `+` pops both and pushes 3
#   - `dup *` duplicates 3 then multiplies the two 3s, leaving 9
#
# min is distinct from every other language documented in the corpus
# because:
#
#   * It is the FIRST documented CONCATENATIVE/STACK-BASED LANGUAGE in
#     the taxonomy.  Forth implementations (gforth, pforth) exist on
#     disk but Forth itself is not currently a documented language
#     entry.  Factor (in corpus) is concatenative but documented under
#     a different angle.  min is the first PRIMARILY-CONCATENATIVE
#     language with full CLI documentation.
#   * It uses HOMOICONIC LIST SYNTAX — `(1 2 3 +)` is a list containing
#     three numbers and the `+` symbol, NOT immediately evaluated.
#     Quoting via parentheses + dispatch via `apply` is min's metaprogramming
#     primitive.  This is the LISP-style homoiconicity layered ON TOP OF
#     stack-based semantics.
#   * It has FIRST-CLASS DICTIONARIES — `{name: "Alice" age: 30}` is a
#     dictionary literal; dictionaries are first-class values that can
#     be stored, passed, modified.  Most concatenative languages don't
#     have first-class dicts; min adds them.
#   * It has a MANAGED MODULE MANAGER (MMM) — `min install some-module`
#     downloads from a curated registry at https://mmm.h3rald.com.
#     Modules can be local-scoped or global, version-pinned, and have
#     dependencies.  This is the FIRST documented "stack-based language
#     with managed-module package manager" — Forth/Factor have library
#     systems but no centralized package registry.
#   * It SHIPS A SHELL MODE — `min -i` enters an interactive shell with
#     min as the command language (not just a REPL).  You can do daily
#     shell tasks using min's syntax: pipes, redirection, glob patterns
#     all work via min's standard library.
#   * It can BE COMPILED VIA NIM — `min compile foo.min` produces a
#     native executable by translating min code to Nim and invoking the
#     Nim compiler.  This is unique among interpreters — a concatenative
#     language with AOT-native-compile support.
#
# min's IMPLEMENTATION LANGUAGE is Nim — Fabio chose Nim for the small
# binary size, easy cross-compilation, and native LLVM backend.  Nim's
# stdlib provides the CLI parsing infrastructure that min uses for its
# own command-line interface.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# MIN'S CLI LIBRARY — Nim std/parseopt OPTPARSER
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# min's CLI parser uses Nim's stdlib `std/parseopt` module.  It is the
# FIRST documented "Nim stdlib parseopt OptParser" pattern in the corpus's
# cross-language taxonomy via a language whose host runtime is Nim.
#
# THE std/parseopt API (verbatim from min.nim):
#
#     import std/parseopt
#
#     var p = initOptParser()
#
#     for kind, key, val in getopt(p):
#         case kind:
#             of cmdArgument:
#                 args.add key
#                 if file == "":
#                     file = key
#             of cmdLongOption, cmdShortOption:
#                 case key:
#                     of "module-path", "m":
#                         MODULEPATH = val
#                     of "asset-path", "a":
#                         ASSETPATH = val
#                     of "global", "g":
#                         GLOBAL = true
#                     of "help", "h":
#                         echo usage
#                         terminate(0)
#                     # ...
#                     else:
#                         discard
#             else:
#                 discard
#
# Distinctive properties:
#
#   1. THREE-VARIANT KIND DISCRIMINATOR — Nim parseopt's `getopt`
#      iterator yields `(kind, key, val)` tuples where `kind` is one of
#      `cmdArgument | cmdLongOption | cmdShortOption | cmdEnd`.  The
#      caller pattern-matches on `kind` to dispatch between positional
#      args and flags.  This is similar to Rust's lexopt (R407) Iterator
#      pattern but with explicit kind tagging instead of separate enum
#      variants.
#
#   2. ITERATOR-BASED PARSING — `for kind, key, val in getopt(p)` runs
#      a single forward iteration over argv.  No flag-registration
#      table, no spec data, no schema.  The caller dispatches on
#      flag NAME inside the iterator body.  This is the Nim equivalent
#      of Rust's getargs (R471) and noargs (R474) but with Nim's tuple-
#      unpacking syntax for the loop variable.
#
#   3. SHORT-AND-LONG DEPENDENT IN-MATCH HANDLING — by pattern-matching
#      `key` against `"module-path", "m"` (multiple alternatives in one
#      `of` branch), the caller treats short and long form identically.
#      This is the CANONICAL idiom in min's parser.  Pure Nim — no
#      external libraries needed.
#
#   4. STDLIB-ONLY DESIGN — `std/parseopt` is part of Nim's standard
#      library since Nim 0.6 (2014).  No external dependency, no semver
#      churn, ships with every Nim install.  Comparable to Python's
#      argparse, Go's flag stdlib, OCaml's Arg — the "always available"
#      CLI library.
#
#   5. NO HELP/USAGE AUTO-GENERATION — Nim parseopt doesn't generate
#      `--help` output.  Callers print their own help string (min uses
#      a multi-line `let usage = """..."""`).  This is consistent with
#      Nim's "stdlib provides primitives, not frameworks" philosophy.
#      Compare argparse (Python stdlib) which auto-generates --help.
#
#   6. AUTO-NORMALIZATION OF KEYS — Nim's `parseopt` normalizes long
#      option names: `--module-path` and `--modulepath` (with hyphen
#      removed) and `--Module_Path` (case-insensitive with underscore-
#      hyphen equivalence) all match the same `"module-path"` key in
#      the case statement.  This is the NIM STYLE INSENSITIVITY rule
#      that applies to all identifiers in Nim, extended to CLI flag
#      names.  Unique among documented CLI libraries — no other has
#      style-insensitive flag matching by default.
#
# CONTRAST WITH OTHER NIM CLI LIBRARIES (NOT YET DOCUMENTED IN CORPUS)
#
# Nim has several CLI libraries beyond std/parseopt:
#
#   * cligen (c-blake/cligen) — derives CLI from proc signatures
#     (similar to clap-derive in Rust, structopt R486)
#   * argparse (iffy/cligen-alt) — Python-argparse-clone in Nim
#   * docopt.nim — Docopt port to Nim
#   * commandeer — declarative CLI framework
#
# std/parseopt (THIS) is the STDLIB minimal layer that other Nim CLI
# libraries are built on top of.  cligen, for example, uses parseopt
# internally and adds the derive-from-proc-signature layer.
#
# CONTRAST WITH OTHER STDLIB MINIMAL CLI PARSERS IN THE TAXONOMY
#
#   * Python argparse                — declarative, auto-help
#   * Go flag (stdlib)               — fixed-signature, no aliases
#   * OCaml Arg                      — list of (name, action, doc)
#   * Java getopts (none in stdlib)  — third-party only
#   * Nim std/parseopt (THIS)        — iterator-based, kind-discriminator,
#                                     style-insensitive matching
#
# Nim parseopt is most similar in spirit to **Java 1.0-era getopt
# ports** — minimal primitives that user code wraps into higher-level
# patterns.  But its STYLE-INSENSITIVITY (matching `--module-path` ==
# `--modulepath` == `--Module_Path`) is a Nim-language-specific feature
# that no other documented stdlib CLI parser has.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# MIN'S CLI SURFACE (verbatim from min.nim usage string)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# USAGE:
#   min [options] [filename | command] [...command-arguments]
#
# Arguments:
#   filename            A .min or .mn file to interpret or compile
#   command             A min command (see below)
#
# Commands:
#   compile <file>      Compile <file>.min to a native executable via Nim
#   eval <string>       Evaluate <string> as a min program
#   help <symbol|sigil> Print the help contents related to <symbol> or
#                       <sigil> (e.g., `min help :` for symbol assignment)
#   init                Sets up the current directory as a managed min module
#   install [<module>@<version>]
#                       Install the specified managed min module or all
#                       dependencies from min.json
#   uninstall [<module>@<version>]
#                       Uninstall a managed min module
#   update [<module>@<version>]
#                       Update a managed min module
#   run <mmm>           Execute the main symbol exposed by the specified
#                       managed min module (downloads + installs globally
#                       if not already present)
#   search [...terms...]
#                       Search the MMM registry for matching modules
#   list                List all managed min modules installed locally or globally
#
# Options:
#   -a, --asset-path <dir>      Asset files to include in compiled exe (-c)
#   -d, --dev                   Enable development mode (runtime checks)
#   -g, --global                Execute install/uninstall globally
#   -h, --help                  Print help
#   -i, --interactive           Start min shell with advanced prompt
#                               (default if no file specified)
#   -j, --interactive-simple    Start min shell without advanced prompt
#   -l, --log <level>           Log level: debug|info|notice|warn|error|fatal
#                               (default: notice)
#   -m, --module-path <dir>     .min files to include in compiled exe
#   -n, --passN <opts>          Pass options to the Nim compiler (with -c)
#   -p, --prelude=<file.min>    Load <file.min> instead of default prelude
#   -r, --registry=<url>        Use <url> as MMM registry instead of default
#   -v, --version               Print version
#
# =============================================================================

_min() {
    local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
    typeset -A opt_args

    local -a subcommands log_levels

    subcommands=(
        'compile:compile a .min file to native executable via Nim'
        'eval:evaluate a min program string'
        'help:print help for a symbol or sigil'
        'init:setup current directory as managed min module'
        'install:install managed min module or dependencies'
        'uninstall:uninstall managed min module'
        'update:update managed min module'
        'run:execute managed min module main symbol'
        'search:search MMM registry'
        'list:list installed managed min modules'
    )

    log_levels=(
        'debug:debug-level logs'
        'info:informational logs'
        'notice:notice logs (default)'
        'warn:warnings only'
        'error:errors only'
        'fatal:fatal errors only'
    )

    _arguments -C \
        '(-a --asset-path)'{-a,--asset-path}'[asset directory for compilation]:dir:_directories' \
        '(-d --dev)'{-d,--dev}'[enable development mode (runtime checks)]' \
        '(-g --global)'{-g,--global}'[execute install/uninstall globally]' \
        '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[print help]' \
        '(-i --interactive)'{-i,--interactive}'[start min shell (advanced prompt)]' \
        '(-j --interactive-simple)'{-j,--interactive-simple}'[start min shell (simple prompt)]' \
        '(-l --log)'{-l,--log}'[log level]:level:->log' \
        '(-m --module-path)'{-m,--module-path}'[module-path directory for compilation]:dir:_directories' \
        '(-n --passN)'{-n,--passN}'[pass options to Nim compiler]:nim opts:' \
        '(-p --prelude)'{-p,--prelude}'[custom prelude file]:prelude:_files -g "*.min"' \
        '(-r --registry)'{-r,--registry}'[MMM registry URL override]:url:' \
        '(-v --version)'{-v,--version}'[print version]' \
        '1: :->cmd' \
        '*::arg:->args' && ret=0

    case $state in
        (log)
            _describe -t log_levels 'log level' log_levels && ret=0
            ;;
        (cmd)
            _alternative \
                'subcommands:command:(($subcommands))' \
                'min-files:min file:_files -g "*.(min|mn)"' \
                && ret=0
            ;;
        (args)
            case $line[1] in
                (compile|eval|init)
                    _files -g "*.(min|mn)" && ret=0
                    ;;
                (install|uninstall|update|run)
                    _message '<module>@<version>' && ret=0
                    ;;
                (search)
                    _message 'search terms' && ret=0
                    ;;
                (help)
                    _message 'symbol or sigil' && ret=0
                    ;;
                (*)
                    _default && ret=0
                    ;;
            esac
            ;;
    esac

    return ret
}

_min "$@"
